                          PREAMBLE

This license is based on the GNU General Public License, version 2
(GPL-2.0), with one additional requirement: the Brand Protection
Clause (Section 11). The intent of this license is to guarantee your
freedom to share, study, modify, and redistribute the W0rkTree
software — while preventing third parties from rebranding the
codebase and passing it off as their own product.

The freedoms guaranteed by the GPL are fully preserved here. You can
read the code, learn from it, modify it, contribute to it, build on
top of it, and redistribute it — provided you keep the source open
and respect the identity of the project you are building upon.

The Brand Protection Clause does NOT restrict your ability to:
  - Use W0rkTree internally for any purpose
  - Create and distribute modified versions of W0rkTree
  - Build commercial products and services that use W0rkTree
  - Fork the repository for your own development purposes
  - Contribute patches, features, and improvements back to W0rkTree

The Brand Protection Clause DOES require that if you redistribute a
modified version, you must not present it as if it were an
independent, original product. You must preserve attribution to the
W0rkTree project. You may add your own name and branding alongside
the original attribution, but you may not remove or replace it.

This is the same principle that protects Firefox (Mozilla), Red Hat
Enterprise Linux, and other open-source projects that are free
software but not free trademarks. The code is open. The name is not
up for grabs.

