  11. BRAND PROTECTION CLAUSE.

This section constitutes the sole additional requirement imposed by
this License beyond the terms of the GNU General Public License,
version 2. It exists to protect the identity of the W0rkTree project
while fully preserving every freedom guaranteed by the GPL.

    a) ATTRIBUTION PRESERVATION. Any Modified Version that you
    distribute or make publicly available must retain clear,
    prominent, and unmodified attribution to the W0rkTree project in
    the following locations, to the extent they exist in your
    Modified Version:

        i)   The primary README or equivalent documentation file
             distributed with the software.

        ii)  Any "About" dialog, help screen, splash screen, or
             equivalent user-facing informational display in a
             graphical or terminal user interface.

        iii) The source code license headers, copyright notices, and
             this License file itself.

    The attribution must state, at minimum:

        "Based on W0rkTree (https://github.com/LegionEdge/worktree),
         licensed under the W0rkTree Public License v1.0."

    You may add your own name, branding, and notices alongside
    this attribution. You may NOT remove, replace, obscure, or
    diminish this attribution.

    b) NO REBRANDING. You may NOT Rebrand the Program or any
    Modified Version. Specifically, you may not:

        i)   Remove or replace the W0rkTree name, logos, or identity
             from the Program and substitute your own branding so as
             to present the result as an original or independent
             product.

        ii)  Register, claim, or assert trademark rights over any
             name, logo, or identity that is confusingly similar to
             the W0rkTree Marks in connection with a Modified Version
             of the Program.

        iii) Distribute a Modified Version under a name designed to
             create the impression that it is not derived from or
             related to W0rkTree when it is, in fact, substantially
             based on the Program.

    c) PERMITTED USES OF THE NAME. For the avoidance of doubt, the
    following uses are expressly permitted and do not constitute
    Rebranding:

        i)   Using the W0rkTree name to truthfully describe the
             origin of your Modified Version (e.g., "MyProject,
             built on W0rkTree" or "MyProject — a W0rkTree
             derivative").

        ii)  Using the W0rkTree name in factual comparative
             statements, reviews, benchmarks, academic research, and
             commentary.

        iii) Using the W0rkTree name in the package metadata, build
             scripts, dependency declarations, and internal source
             code identifiers of your Modified Version, provided such
             use does not imply endorsement by or affiliation with
             the W0rkTree project unless such endorsement or
             affiliation actually exists.

        iv)  Distributing an unmodified copy of the Program under its
             original name.

        v)   Creating internal forks, private modifications, and
             non-distributed copies for personal, educational, or
             organizational use without any naming restrictions
             whatsoever.

        vi)  Building and distributing plugins, extensions, tools,
             libraries, and services that interoperate with W0rkTree,
             under any name you choose, provided they are separate
             works and not Rebranded copies of the Program itself.

    d) DISTINGUISHING MODIFIED VERSIONS. If you distribute a
    Modified Version publicly, you must distinguish it from the
    original Program by:

        i)   Using a name that either includes "W0rkTree" with a
             distinguishing modifier (e.g., "W0rkTree Community
             Edition," "W0rkTree-Enhanced," "MyOrg's W0rkTree") OR
             a clearly different name accompanied by the attribution
             required in Section 11(a) (e.g., "MyProject — based on
             W0rkTree").

        ii)  Including a prominent notice in the README or equivalent
             documentation stating that the software is a modified
             version of W0rkTree, describing the nature of the
             modifications at a summary level.

    e) ENFORCEMENT AND REMEDIES. Violation of this Section 11
    constitutes a breach of this License. Upon breach, the
    copyright holders may, at their sole discretion:

        i)   Provide written notice of the violation and a thirty
             (30) day cure period during which you may come into
             compliance.

        ii)  If the violation is not cured within the cure period,
             terminate your rights under this License as provided in
             Section 4.

    Cure is possible for all violations of this section. Good-faith
    efforts to comply (such as adding missing attribution, renaming
    a product, or updating documentation) are sufficient to cure a
    violation within the cure period.

    f) SCOPE LIMITATION. This Section 11 applies solely to the
    distribution and public presentation of Modified Versions. It
    does not restrict:

        i)   Private use, internal use, or non-distributed
             modifications in any way.

        ii)  The functional modification, improvement, extension, or
             adaptation of the Program's source code for any purpose.

        iii) The creation of interoperable software, competing
             products built from scratch, or clean-room
             implementations of the W0rkTree protocol specification.

        iv)  Fair use, free speech, commentary, criticism, or
             reverse engineering as permitted by applicable law.

    This section is intended to be the minimum restriction necessary
    to prevent misappropriation of the project's identity. It is
    not intended to limit the open-source nature of the Program in
    any other way.

